      "id": "article",
      "master": "mag",
      "lang": "en-US",
      "story": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 1,
          "text": "On the Physics of Iridescence",
          "style": "h1",
          "set_string": [
            {
              "name": "section",
              "value": "Iridescence"
            }
          ],
          "id": "h-irid"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "By the Optics Desk",
          "style": "byline"
        },
        {
          "type": "spacer",
          "height": "6px"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            {
              "text": "I",
              "style": "dropcap"
            },
            "ridescence is structural color: hue produced not by pigment but by the way light interferes with itself across features the size of its own wavelength. Tilt the surface and the color shifts — the signature that geometry, not chemistry, is doing the work."
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "In a thin film, light reflects from both the top and bottom surfaces. The two reflected waves travel paths that differ by twice the film thickness, and where that difference is a whole number of wavelengths the waves reinforce; elsewhere they cancel. Because the condition depends on wavelength, each thickness favors a particular color.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "block",
          "role": "pullquote",
          "style": "pullblock",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "Color you can tilt: the hue lives in the geometry, not in the pigment.",
              "style": "pull"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "spans": [
            "The same mechanism paints the soap bubble, the beetle's shell, and the ",
            {
              "text": "compact-disc",
              "style": "link"
            },
            " sheen. Engineers exploit it deliberately in ",
            {
              "text": "dielectric mirrors",
              "style": "sc"
            },
            ", stacking dozens of quarter-wave layers so that a chosen band reflects almost perfectly while the rest passes through."
          ],
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "block",
          "role": "note",
          "style": "callout",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "Field Note",
              "style": "co_label"
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "To see thin-film color at home, float a drop of oil on a puddle. The film thins as it spreads, so the bands of color map directly onto thickness.",
              "style": "co_body"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The table below pairs film thickness with the hue it reflects most strongly at normal incidence, for a film of refractive index near 1.4.",
          "style": "body"
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "header": [
            {
              "content": "Thickness (nm)",
              "style": "th"
            },
            {
              "content": "Reflected hue",
              "style": "th"
            },
            {
              "content": "Everyday example",
              "style": "th"
            }
          ],
          "columns": [
            {
              "width": "30%",
              "align": "left"
            },
            {
              "width": "30%",
              "align": "left"
            },
            {
              "width": "40%",
              "align": "left"
            }
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              {
                "content": "~110",
                "style": "cell"
              },
